# SastaSpace - Cursor AI Configuration

## Project Context
- Rails 8.1 application with Hotwire frontend
- PostgreSQL + pgvector for AI features
- Local AI via Ollama (no API costs)
- Testing: Minitest, Capybara, VCR, Mocha
- CI: Rubocop, Brakeman, Simplecov
- Background Jobs: Sidekiq with Redis

## Coding Standards
1. **Always use TDD**: Write tests before implementation
2. **Rails Conventions**: Follow RESTful routing, use generators
3. **No Fat Controllers**: Move business logic to services
4. **Hotwire-First**: Use Turbo Frames/Streams, avoid custom JS unless necessary
5. **Service Objects**: Plain Ruby classes in `app/services/` for business logic
6. **Background Jobs**: Use Sidekiq workers in `app/jobs/` for async tasks

## File Structure
- Models: `app/models/` (ActiveRecord only, no business logic)
- Services: `app/services/` (POROs for business logic)
- Jobs: `app/jobs/` (Sidekiq workers for async tasks)
- Controllers: `app/controllers/` (RESTful actions only)
- API Controllers: `app/controllers/api/v1/` (namespaced)

## Pre-Commit Checklist
```bash
bin/rubocop --autocorrect-all
bin/brakeman --quiet
bin/rails test
```

## Common Patterns

### Service Object Template
```ruby
# app/services/quota_enforcer.rb
class QuotaEnforcer
  class QuotaExceededError < StandardError; end

  def initialize(user)
    @user = user
  end

  def check!(resource_type)
    return true if @user.premium?

    current_count = @user.send(resource_type).count
    limit = LIMITS[@user.plan_type][resource_type]

    raise QuotaExceededError if current_count >= limit
    true
  end

  private

  LIMITS = {
    free: { inventory_items: 50, outfits: 10 },
    premium: { inventory_items: Float::INFINITY, outfits: Float::INFINITY }
  }.freeze
end
```

### Controller Action Template
```ruby
# app/controllers/inventory_items_controller.rb
def create
  QuotaEnforcer.new(current_user).check!(:inventory_items)

  @inventory_item = current_user.inventory_items.build(inventory_item_params)

  if @inventory_item.save
    redirect_to @inventory_item, notice: "Item added!"
  else
    render :new, status: :unprocessable_entity
  end
rescue QuotaEnforcer::QuotaExceededError
  redirect_to upgrade_path, alert: "Quota exceeded. Upgrade to Premium!"
end
```

### Test Template (Minitest)
```ruby
# test/services/quota_enforcer_test.rb
require "test_helper"

class QuotaEnforcerTest < ActiveSupport::TestCase
  setup do
    @user = users(:free_user)
    @enforcer = QuotaEnforcer.new(@user)
  end

  test "allows creation under quota" do
    assert @enforcer.check!(:inventory_items)
  end

  test "raises error when quota exceeded" do
    create_list(:inventory_item, 50, user: @user)

    assert_raises(QuotaEnforcer::QuotaExceededError) do
      @enforcer.check!(:inventory_items)
    end
  end

  test "allows unlimited for premium users" do
    @user.update!(plan_type: :premium)
    create_list(:inventory_item, 100, user: @user)

    assert @enforcer.check!(:inventory_items)
  end
end
```

### API Controller Template
```ruby
# app/controllers/api/v1/base_controller.rb
class Api::V1::BaseController < ApplicationController
  include ApiResponse
  include ErrorHandling
  include Authenticable

  before_action :authenticate_user!
  before_action :set_pagination_params

  private

  def set_pagination_params
    @page = params[:page] || 1
    @per_page = [params[:per_page]&.to_i || 25, 100].min
  end
end
```

### Background Job Template
```ruby
# app/jobs/process_image_embedding_job.rb
class ProcessImageEmbeddingJob < ApplicationJob
  queue_as :ai_critical
  include TrackableJob

  def perform(inventory_item_id)
    item = InventoryItem.find(inventory_item_id)
    EmbeddingService.new.generate_and_store(item)
  rescue ActiveRecord::RecordNotFound => e
    Rails.logger.error("InventoryItem #{inventory_item_id} not found: #{e.message}")
  end
end
```

## Testing Guidelines

### Avoid Hard-Coding in Tests
**Critical Rule**: Never hard-code values in tests that could cause collisions.

1. **Use Unique Identifiers**: Always use `SecureRandom.hex(4)`, `SecureRandom.uuid`, or FactoryBot sequences
   ```ruby
   # ❌ BAD: Hard-coded name can collide
   category = create(:category, name: "T-Shirts")
   
   # ✅ GOOD: Unique name using SecureRandom
   unique_name = "T-Shirts #{SecureRandom.hex(4)}"
   category = create(:category, name: unique_name)
   ```

2. **Use Unique File Paths**: For temp files, file paths, or mock paths
   ```ruby
   # ❌ BAD: Hard-coded path
   existing_path = "/tmp/existing_path.jpg"
   
   # ✅ GOOD: Unique path
   existing_path = "/tmp/existing_path_#{SecureRandom.hex(4)}.jpg"
   ```

3. **Stub Order Matters**: When stubbing methods on an object, stub dependent methods BEFORE stubbing methods that return mocks/substitutes
   ```ruby
   # ✅ GOOD: Stub blob methods before stubbing service
   @image_blob.stubs(:download).returns("fake data")
   @image_blob.stubs(:content_type).returns("image/jpeg")
   @image_blob.stubs(:service).returns(mock_service)
   ```

### AI Response Parsing (Critical!)
- **NEVER assume AI models return perfect JSON** - they often include explanatory text, "thinking out loud", or markdown formatting
- **Implement multi-strategy JSON extraction**:
  1. Extract between first `{` and last `}`
  2. Look for JSON in markdown code fences (`` ```json ... ``` ``)
  3. Use line-by-line brace counting for complex cases
- **Test with real-world AI responses** - not just perfect `.to_json` output
- **Add production error cases to test suite immediately** when discovered

## Commands for Cursor
- "Generate tests for this service"
- "Refactor this controller action following Rails conventions"
- "Add database migration for [feature]"
- "Create Turbo Frame for this UI component"
- "Review this code for Rails best practices and security issues"

## Agent Workflow Integration

### When Acting as Code-Agent
1. Read architecture comment from GitHub issue
2. Create feature branch: `git checkout -b feature/issue-#{issue_number}-short-name`
3. Write failing tests first (TDD)
4. Implement minimal code to pass
5. Run `bin/ci` before committing
6. Create PR with proper description and labels

### When Acting as Review-Agent
1. Check automated checks (Rubocop, Brakeman, Tests)
2. Review for Rails conventions
3. Check for N+1 queries (Bullet gem)
4. Verify security (authorization, input validation)
5. Post review comments with inline suggestions

### When Acting as Arch-Agent
1. Analyze issue requirements
2. Design database schema changes
3. Plan service objects and controllers
4. Consider background job needs
5. Post architecture comment on issue

## Security Checklist
- [ ] Authorization checks present (`authorize @resource`)
- [ ] Strong params validated
- [ ] No raw SQL (or properly sanitized)
- [ ] File uploads validated (size, type)
- [ ] Rate limiting applied where needed

## Performance Checklist
- [ ] No N+1 queries detected
- [ ] Database indexes added for new queries
- [ ] Background job used for slow operations
- [ ] Caching strategy considered
